odd.head: General note
odd.p: Forms part of Yale Record Group 12-A (YRG 12-A), Central records and records of the dean of the Yale Freshman Year.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Access to the records is restricted. See Collection Contents for details.

arrangement.p: The records are arranged alphabetically by subject.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Following the end of World War I, Yale alumni requested that a freshman year program, with its own dean and faculty, be established as a type of junior college for incoming students. Despite some faculty disagreement, the Freshman Year was approved in 1919. Its aims were to prevent a student from having to choose between Sheffield Scientific School and Yale College before arrival at Yale and to give more attention to the needs of freshmen during the transitional year between secondary school and college. Although the first goal was accomplished, the success of the second became increasingly problematic with the changing curriculum during the 1920s and 1930s. In response to complaints that the program was becoming too isolated from the College, the curriculum began to resemble that of Yale College itself. By 1938, courses were no longer prescribed and, for the first time since the beginning of the Freshman Year, students were encouraged to choose courses in connection with their fields of concentration.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The records consist of administrative files, primarily of Dean Harold B. Whiteman, documenting the activities and operations of the Yale Freshman Year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Box 1 contains indices for each year from 1920-1957. Occassionally code numbers were re-used for other subjects, therefore the indices must be consulted.
